<span id="freeTextContainer16519466392435279298">Two space travelers (one from Sirius, one from Saturn), gigantic in size (when they step into the deepest parts of our oceans only their ankles or shins are covered) come to Earth, learn French in three hours, and have a silly conversation with a boatload of philosophers. Typical Voltairean caustic wit, pessimism, and intellectualism.<br/><br/>Favorite part: When the giant space visitors finally become aware that on this strange planet they&apos;ve come to (Earth) there are living specks (humans) visible to th</span>
  <span id="freeText16519466392435279298" style="display:none">Two space travelers (one from Sirius, one from Saturn), gigantic in size (when they step into the deepest parts of our oceans only their ankles or shins are covered) come to Earth, learn French in three hours, and have a silly conversation with a boatload of philosophers. Typical Voltairean caustic wit, pessimism, and intellectualism.<br /><br />Favorite part: When the giant space visitors finally become aware that on this strange planet they've come to (Earth) there are living specks (humans) visible to them only through "microscopes", one says, "I see more than ever that one must not judge anything by its apparent size." Fast-forward two hundred years to Dr. Seuss and Horton: "A person's a person no matter how small." More than coincidence?</span>
