<div id="review_1128307449" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1128307449" />
    <a title="Vishal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27248823-vishal"><img alt="Vishal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1418477422p2/27248823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1128307449?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vishal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vishal" href="/user/show/27248823-vishal">Vishal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27248823-vishal?shelf=satire">satire</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1128307449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11493216787229014237">A short story emulating Gullivers&apos; Travels in the aspect that humans are shown from a perspective of other beings. In the story, a being from Sirius and another from Saturn -both colossal with respect to puny humans- happen to come to Earth and discover it to be inhabited by humans. They contrive some means to have conversations with humans, exchange philosophical ideas and get astonished at the capability of reason and intellect shown by such tiny creatures. But when they learn of human evils, </span>
  <span id="freeText11493216787229014237" style="display:none">A short story emulating Gullivers' Travels in the aspect that humans are shown from a perspective of other beings. In the story, a being from Sirius and another from Saturn -both colossal with respect to puny humans- happen to come to Earth and discover it to be inhabited by humans. They contrive some means to have conversations with humans, exchange philosophical ideas and get astonished at the capability of reason and intellect shown by such tiny creatures. But when they learn of human evils, wars and massacres; they get revolted and appalled by such character of extreme violence and fury to have been bestowed by the Nature to such insignificant beings. Micromegas, the Sirian inhabitant, then offers the humans a valuable book which encompasses the knowledge of philosophy and the point of all things we do.<br /><br />The story is only 38 pages long and very simply written. I will suggest it to everyone who is reading this review, it won't take more than an hour and could be read without straining your comprehension abilities. Beauty of the story lies in its simplicity, lucidity and witty humor which blend in with some great lessons for humans.<br /><br />PS: I'll be more than happy if people would stop tagging this story as a science-fiction story, it doesn't become related to science just because it involves aliens. Also, people need to stop propagating Voltaire and Jonathan Swift as the ones who had made the prophecy of Mars having two moons. Voltaire states the Mars has two tiny moons, which turns out to be true, but his every other speculations about planets turned out to be wrong. This is a very remarkable satirical and philosophical story and should be regarded as such. It has nothing to do with Science-fiction.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11493216787229014237" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


